:::summary
The Age of Exploration (roughly 1415–1620) was the era when European navigators, sponsored by the kingdoms of Portugal and Spain and later England, France, and the Netherlands, sailed beyond the known world to map the coasts of Africa, reach India by sea, encounter the Americas, and circumnavigate the globe. It was one of the most consequential periods in human history, inaugurating a new era of global commerce, cultural encounter, missionary endeavor, and — tragically — conquest and the Atlantic slave trade.
:::

